VALUES
(44, 23, 1, 44, 24, 16, 16, 'good conscience before God', 'Conscience Before God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining a good conscience before God. Paul expresses his commitment to living with a clear conscience in both instances, highlighting its significance in his life and ministry.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 1, 47, 1, 12, 12, 'good conscience', 'Conscience and Sincerity Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of a clear conscience. Paul speaks of living in good conscience before God, while he also highlights the testimony of their conscience in sincerity.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 1, 55, 1, 3, 3, 'good conscience', 'Connection of Conscience in Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of serving God with a pure or good conscience. Paul expresses his commitment to living with a clear conscience before God, which resonates with his gratitude for serving with a pure conscience in 2 Timothy.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 1, 58, 13, 18, 18, 'good conscience', 'Conscience and Honest Living', 'This connection highlights the theme of maintaining a good conscience before God. Both passages emphasize the importance of living honestly and with integrity in one''s actions.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 1, 46, 4, 4, 4, 'good conscience before God', 'Conscience and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of conscience and judgment. Paul asserts his good conscience before God in Acts, while in Corinthians, he acknowledges that ultimate judgment belongs to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 1, 44, 22, 5, 5, 'good conscience before God', 'Paul''s Conscience and Witness', 'This connection highlights Paul''s assertion of a clear conscience before God, which relates to his previous actions in Acts 22:5 where he received letters to persecute Christians. Both passages emphasize Paul''s commitment to his beliefs and the testimony of others regarding his past.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 1, 20, 28, 1, 1, 'good conscience', 'Boldness and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of boldness in both passages. Paul’s declaration of having lived in ''good conscience'' reflects the confidence of the ''righteous'' who are ''bold as a lion.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 2, 43, 18, 22, 22, 'smite him on the mouth', 'Striking of the Mouth', 'This connection highlights the act of striking a figure of authority. Both passages describe a physical assault on individuals in a judicial context, emphasizing the treatment of those accused before the high priest.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 2, 44, 24, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Ananias'' Actions', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Ananias'' role as high priest in both passages. In Acts 23:2, Ananias commands violence against Paul, while in Acts 24:1, he is involved in the formal accusation against Paul.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 2, 11, 22, 24, 24, 'smite him on the mouth', 'Physical Assault on Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the act of smiting a prophet, highlighting the hostility faced by those delivering God''s message. In Acts, Ananias commands to smite, while in 1 Kings, Zedekiah smites Micaiah, illustrating a pattern of violence against prophetic voices.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 2, 33, 5, 1, 1, 'smite him on the mouth', 'Connection of Smiting References', 'Both passages emphasize the act of being smitten, specifically referencing a judge or leader. In Acts, Ananias commands to ''smite him on the mouth,'' while Micah foretells that they ''shall smite the judge of Israel with a rod upon the cheek.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 2, 24, 20, 2, 2, 'smite him on the mouth', 'Violence Against Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of violence against prophets in both passages. In Acts, Ananias commands to ''smite him on the mouth,'' while in Jeremiah, Pashur ''smote Jeremiah the prophet.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 2, 40, 26, 67, 67, 'smite him on the mouth', 'Physical Violence Against Figures', 'Both passages emphasize acts of physical violence against individuals. In Acts, Ananias commands to ''smite him on the mouth,'' while in Matthew, Jesus is subjected to being ''smote...with the palms of their hands.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 5, 25, 1, 2, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Punishment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and punishment. Both passages address the role of judges in determining guilt and administering punishment, emphasizing the need for lawful conduct in judgment.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 43, 7, 51, 51, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Legal Process', 'This connection highlights the theme of legal judgment in both passages. Paul questions the legality of his treatment, while the question in John emphasizes the need for hearing before judgment.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 40, 23, 27, 28, 'whited wall', 'Hypocrisy and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in both passages. Paul refers to the high priest as a ''whited wall,'' paralleling Jesus'' description of the Pharisees as ''whited sepulchres,'' both emphasizing outward appearances versus inner corruption.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 3, 19, 15, 15, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteous judgment. In Acts, Paul condemns the unjust treatment he receives, while Leviticus emphasizes the importance of not showing favoritism in judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 3, 19, 35, 35, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of unrighteous judgment. Paul''s accusation of being judged contrary to the law resonates with the call for righteousness in judgment found in Leviticus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 19, 58, 1, 2, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Wickedness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of unjust judgment. Both passages emphasize the idea of judging contrary to righteousness, with Acts 23:3 referencing a wrongful judgment and Psalms 58:1-2 questioning the integrity of judgment among men.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 19, 82, 1, 2, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Injustice Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of unjust judgment present in both passages. Paul accuses the high priest of judging him contrary to the law, paralleling the call in Psalms to judge justly and not accept the persons of the wicked.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 2, 22, 28, 28, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people.', 'Connection of Rulers in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition against speaking ill of leaders. Acts 23:5 directly quotes the principle found in Exodus 22:28 regarding rulers of the people.', 'quotation', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 21, 10, 20, 20, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people', 'Respect for Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of refraining from speaking ill of rulers. Both passages emphasize the importance of respecting authority figures, whether in public or private thoughts.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 65, 1, 8, 9, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people', 'Respect for Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of not speaking evil against authority figures. Both passages emphasize the importance of showing respect towards dignities and rulers, as seen in Paul''s reference to the high priest and Michael''s restraint against the devil.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 61, 2, 10, 10, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people', 'Connection on Speaking Evil of Rulers', 'This connection highlights the theme of speaking against authority. Both passages emphasize the importance of respecting rulers and the consequences of despising government.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 44, 24, 17, 17, 'ruler of thy people', 'Connection of Leadership and Offerings', 'This connection highlights the theme of respect for authority and the act of bringing offerings. In Acts 23:5, Paul acknowledges the ruler''s position, while in Acts 24:17, he speaks of bringing alms to his nation, suggesting a relationship between leadership and communal support.', 'theme', 0.244, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 44, 24, 15, 15, 'resurrection of the dead', 'Resurrection of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of resurrection, with Paul identifying himself as a Pharisee who believes in it and expressing hope in a future resurrection. This thematic connection underscores the shared belief in resurrection among different Jewish groups.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 44, 24, 21, 21, 'resurrection of the dead', 'Connection on Resurrection of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection, with Paul explicitly stating he is called in question regarding it. This connection highlights the continuity of Paul''s defense centered on the resurrection across different contexts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 50, 3, 5, 5, 'I am a Pharisee', 'Paul''s Identity as a Pharisee', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s identity as a Pharisee, highlighting his background and beliefs. In Acts, he identifies himself as a Pharisee in relation to the resurrection, while in Philippians, he states his lineage and adherence to the law as a Pharisee.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 40, 22, 23, 23, 'resurrection of the dead', 'Resurrection Debate Between Groups', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of resurrection, with Acts highlighting Paul''s identity as a Pharisee who believes in it, while Matthew presents the Sadducees who deny it. This connection highlights the theological divide between the two groups regarding the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 40, 10, 16, 16, 'the hope and resurrection of the dead', 'Wisdom in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of navigating conflict. Paul identifies himself among opposing groups, demonstrating wisdom in a challenging situation, similar to being ''wise as serpents'' in the face of danger.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 19, 55, 9, 9, NULL, 'Division and Strife in Context', 'Both passages emphasize division and conflict among people. Acts 23:7 describes a division between the Pharisees and Sadducees, while Psalms 55:9 calls for the destruction of tongues due to violence and strife.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 40, 10, 34, 34, 'dissension between the Pharisees and the Sadducees', 'Division and Conflict in Teachings', 'This connection highlights the theme of division present in both passages. Acts 23:7 describes a dissension, while Matthew 10:34 speaks of bringing a sword, indicating conflict rather than peace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 43, 7, 40, 43, 'there arose a dissension', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize division among the people. In Acts, the dissension arises between the Pharisees and Sadducees, while in John, the crowd is divided over Jesus'' identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 44, 14, 4, 4, 'the multitude was divided', 'Division Among Groups', 'Both passages emphasize division within groups, highlighting conflict among differing beliefs. In Acts 23:7, the dissension arises between the Pharisees and Sadducees, while in Acts 14:4, the multitude is divided between Jews and apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 42, 20, 27, 27, NULL, 'Sadducees and Resurrection Denial', 'Both passages emphasize the Sadducees'' denial of resurrection. Acts 23:8 states that the Sadducees say there is no resurrection, which is echoed in Luke 20:27 where they are described as denying any resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 40, 22, 23, 23, NULL, 'Sadducees and Resurrection Beliefs', 'Both passages emphasize the Sadducees'' denial of resurrection. Acts 23:8 explicitly states their belief, while Matthew 22:23 introduces them with the same claim.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 41, 12, 18, 18, 'there is no resurrection', 'Sadducees and Resurrection Beliefs', 'Both passages emphasize the Sadducees'' denial of resurrection. Acts 23:8 states their belief that there is ''no resurrection,'' which is echoed in Mark 12:18. This connection highlights the consistent portrayal of Sadducean theology.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 44, 4, 1, 1, 'no resurrection', 'Sadducees and Resurrection Beliefs', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Sadducees in relation to resurrection beliefs. Acts 23:8 states the Sadducees deny resurrection, while Acts 4:1 shows their presence opposing the apostles.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 44, 22, 7, 7, 'if a spirit or an angel', 'Divine Communication and Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize a divine voice speaking to Saul. The mention of a spirit or angel in Acts 23:9 connects to the voice Saul hears in Acts 22:7, highlighting the theme of divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 44, 22, 17, 18, 'if a spirit or an angel', 'Divine Communication and Response', 'Both passages emphasize divine communication, with Acts 22:17-18 describing a vision from God and Acts 23:9 referencing a spirit or angel. This connection highlights the theme of responding to divine messages, suggesting a continuity in the experience of revelation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 43, 12, 29, 29, NULL, 'Divine Communication Through Angels', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through angels. Both passages mention the idea of an angel speaking, suggesting a shared understanding of spiritual encounters.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 20, 16, 7, 7, 'let us not fight against God', 'Peace with Enemies', 'This connection highlights how divine approval can lead to unexpected harmony, as seen in both passages. In Acts, the Pharisees acknowledge that opposing Paul could mean fighting against God, suggesting that pleasing God can influence even adversaries. Similarly, Proverbs states that when a man''s ways please the Lord, his enemies may be at peace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 41, 2, 16, 16, NULL, 'Conflict with Religious Authorities', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition faced by Jesus from religious leaders. In Acts, the Pharisees defend Paul against accusations, while in Mark, they criticize Jesus for associating with sinners.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 9, 24, 17, 17, 'let us not fight against God', 'Righteousness and Divine Communication', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. In Acts, the Pharisees acknowledge a divine communication, while in 1 Samuel, David is recognized as more righteous despite being wronged.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 42, 5, 30, 30, 'scribes that were of the Pharisees’ part', 'Conflict with Scribes and Pharisees', 'This connection highlights the opposition faced by both Paul and Jesus from the Pharisees and their scribes. In Acts, the Pharisees defend Paul against accusations, while in Luke, they criticize Jesus for associating with sinners.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 44, 22, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection Between Paul''s Arrest', 'Both passages emphasize the chief captain''s actions to protect Paul. In Acts 22:24, he commands Paul to be brought into the castle, while in Acts 23:10, he orders soldiers to take him by force to ensure his safety.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 59, 1, 19, 19, 'great dissension', 'Listening and Responding in Conflict', 'This connection highlights the importance of being ''swift to hear'' in situations of dissension, as seen in both passages. Acts 23:10 describes a chaotic moment where listening and understanding could prevent escalation, while James 1:19 advises a measured response to conflict.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 19, 7, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Danger and Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize the peril of being torn apart. Acts 23:10 describes Paul being rescued from a violent situation, while Psalms 7:2 speaks of a soul being rended like a lion, highlighting a theme of danger and the need for deliverance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 19, 50, 22, 22, NULL, 'Divine Protection and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of being torn apart, as both passages reference the act of tearing in pieces. In Acts, Paul is saved from being torn apart by soldiers, while Psalms warns those who forget God of a similar fate.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 33, 3, 3, 3, 'pulled in pieces', 'Violence Against the Innocent', 'This connection highlights the theme of violence against individuals, as both passages depict the brutal treatment of people. Acts 23:10 describes the threat to Paul’s life, while Micah 3:3 illustrates the violent actions against the innocent.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 44, 19, 28, 31, 'fearing lest Paul should have been pulled in pieces', 'Conflict and Protection of Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the danger Paul faced from a hostile crowd. In Acts 23:10, the chief captain intervenes to protect Paul from being harmed, while in Acts 19:30-31, Paul''s friends prevent him from entering a tumultuous situation, highlighting the need for protection amidst conflict.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 44, 18, 9, 9, NULL, 'Encouragement in Times of Fear', 'Both passages emphasize divine encouragement given to Paul during challenging times. In Acts 23:11, the Lord reassures Paul to be of good cheer, while in Acts 18:9, He instructs Paul not to be afraid.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 44, 19, 21, 21, NULL, 'Paul''s Journey to Rome', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s intention to go to Rome. In Acts 19:21, Paul expresses his desire to see Rome, while Acts 23:11 confirms that he will bear witness there as part of his mission.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 55, 4, 17, 17, NULL, 'Divine Support in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize the Lord''s presence and support during difficult times. In Acts, the Lord encourages Paul, while in 2 Timothy, Paul acknowledges the Lord standing with him.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 40, 14, 27, 27, 'Be of good cheer', 'Encouragement in Times of Fear', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Be of good cheer,'' highlighting a message of encouragement in challenging situations. In Acts, Paul is reassured of his mission, while in Matthew, the disciples are comforted in fear.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 24, 15, 19, 21, NULL, 'Divine Assurance in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise of protection and deliverance during times of trial. In Acts, the Lord assures Paul of his mission in Rome, while in Jeremiah, God promises to deliver Jeremiah from adversaries.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 45, 1, 15, 16, 'bear witness also at Rome', 'Paul''s Mission to Rome', 'This connection highlights Paul''s commitment to preaching in Rome as indicated in both passages. In Acts, the Lord assures Paul of his mission to bear witness in Rome, while in Romans, Paul expresses his readiness to preach the gospel there.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 11, 19, 46, 1, 2, 'Be of good cheer, Paul', 'God''s Presence in Trouble', 'This connection highlights God''s assurance of support in times of distress. Both passages emphasize the theme of divine presence and strength during challenging circumstances.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 44, 23, 30, 30, NULL, 'Plot Against Paul', 'This connection highlights the conspiracy against Paul, as the first passage describes the Jews'' vow to kill him, while the second passage reveals that the authorities were informed of this plot. Both passages emphasize the danger Paul faced from the Jews.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 23, 8, 9, 10, NULL, 'Conspiracy Against Paul and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of conspiratorial actions against a figure of faith. Both passages emphasize the futility of such plots, as those who conspire will ultimately face failure due to divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 44, 23, 21, 21, NULL, 'Oath of the Conspirators', 'Both passages emphasize the oath taken by the conspirators to not eat or drink until they kill Paul. This connection highlights the seriousness of their plot against him and the danger he faces.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 19, 2, 1, 3, NULL, 'Conspiracy Against the Anointed', 'This connection highlights the theme of plotting against God''s chosen. Both passages emphasize the actions of those who conspire to harm the anointed, reflecting a shared defiance against divine authority.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 19, 31, 13, 13, NULL, 'Plot Against Life', 'Both passages emphasize a conspiracy to take away life. Acts 23:12 describes a group plotting to kill Paul, while Psalms 31:13 reflects on slander and counsel against the speaker''s life.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 24, 11, 19, 19, NULL, 'Plot Against Paul and Jeremiah', 'This connection highlights the theme of conspiracies against the innocent. Both passages emphasize the intent to destroy a figure seen as a threat, with Paul facing a plot to kill him and Jeremiah being targeted for his prophetic voice.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 12, 12, 6, 31, 31, 'bound themselves under a curse', 'Curses and Oaths in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of binding oneself under a curse. Both passages involve individuals making serious vows related to life and death situations.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 13, 43, 16, 2, 2, NULL, 'Conspiracy and Persecution Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of conspiracies against believers. Both passages emphasize the idea that those who conspire or persecute do so under the belief they are serving God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 13, 10, 15, 12, 12, NULL, 'Conspiracy and Its Strength', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of conspiracy, highlighting the involvement of a significant number of individuals in plotting against authority. In Acts, the conspiracy involves ''more than forty,'' while in 2 Samuel, the conspiracy is described as ''strong'' with increasing support for Absalom.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 13, 10, 15, 31, 31, 'conspiracy', 'Conspiracy and Counsel', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of conspiracy against a leader. In Acts, a group conspires against Paul, while in 2 Samuel, Ahithophel conspires against David, highlighting the dangers of betrayal.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 44, 23, 12, 12, 'that we will eat nothing until we have slain Paul', 'Cursed Oath Against Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the Jews'' vow to not eat or drink until they kill Paul. This connection highlights their commitment to this deadly plan, illustrating the intensity of their opposition.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 24, 8, 12, 12, NULL, 'Shame and Violence Connection', 'This connection highlights the lack of shame in both passages. In Acts, the conspirators are unashamedly committed to violence against Paul, paralleling the indifference to shame described in Jeremiah.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 19, 52, 1, 2, 'slain Paul', 'Connection of Deceit and Violence', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of deceit and malicious intent. In Acts, the conspirators vow to slay Paul, while Psalms speaks of a tongue that devises mischiefs, highlighting the connection between their violent plans and deceitful speech.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 23, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Sin and Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of conspiring to commit evil, as seen in both passages. The individuals in Acts declare their intent to slay Paul, paralleling the declaration of sin in Isaiah, where evil is rewarded.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 28, 4, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Actions and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of collective responsibility and the consequences of actions. In Acts, the conspirators'' vow to kill Paul reflects a moral failing, while Hosea emphasizes that both people and priests will be punished for their ways.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 33, 7, 3, 3, NULL, 'Evil Intent and Conspiracy', 'This connection highlights the theme of plotting evil against others. Both passages emphasize the deliberate actions taken by individuals to achieve their malicious desires.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 14, 24, 6, 15, 15, NULL, 'Shame and Violence Connection', 'This connection highlights the lack of shame in committing violence. Both passages emphasize a disregard for moral boundaries, as seen in the vow to kill Paul and the abominations mentioned in Jeremiah.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 15, 19, 37, 32, 33, NULL, 'Wickedness Against the Righteous', 'This connection highlights the theme of the wicked plotting against the righteous. In Acts, the wicked seek to kill Paul, paralleling Psalms where the wicked watch and seek to slay the righteous.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 15, 23, 59, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Violence and Iniquity', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shedding innocent blood and the pursuit of evil. Acts 23:15 describes a plot to kill, while Isaiah 59:7 speaks of running to evil and thoughts of iniquity. This connection highlights a thematic parallel of malicious intent and violence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 15, 20, 1, 11, 12, 'ready to kill him', 'Plot Against Innocent Lives', 'This connection highlights the theme of conspiracies against the innocent. Both passages depict a malicious intent to harm the innocent without cause, emphasizing the danger posed by those who plot against others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
